The most basic component for quantuminformation storage and processing is the so-called qubit,
qubits–generally, two or three–gives rise to a logical gate, the most elementary unit in any quantum
algorithm devoted to execute a speciﬁc task. Indeed, an algorithm is nothing but a sequence of
logical gates. The possibility of developing more sophisticated algorithms, hence involving a larger
number of logical gates, critically depends on our ability to entangle an increasing number of qubits
without damaging the encoded information. This is what is known as scalability. For this purpose,
it is crucial to control both the position and the orientation of the relevant physical qubits in space
so that they can properly communicate with each other.
